\
Paper summary\
-------------\
\strike \strikec0 The paper describes the TPTP format suitable for expressing interpretations, i.e. countermodels of theorems in the theorem proving context.\
- Section 1 starts with some applications of such interpretations mentioning verification, consistency checking, etc. as prominent areas of use,and discusses its relation to the TPTP world.\
- Section 2 gives a survey over the interpretation landscape, i.e. what they are needed for, what kinds are there, what is actually supported by ATP systems and TPTP, and what is expected of these interpretations. I\'92m not a model theoretician, so I cannot tell if anything is missing here, but from what I know it looks like a nice summary of the main directions. I also understand that this contains what TPTP aims to support.\
- Section 3 and 4 gives a more thorough account on the (expected) features of Tarskian, resp. Kripke models in detail while also providing a case study with many examples (fully outlined in the appendices).\
- Section 5 concludes with some remarks on adoption of the format and a somewhat ad-hoc account on the authors beliefs on the \'93usefulness\'94 of the presented interpretations.\
\
Overall, I think the paper is well-written and has enough practical aspects for ATPs to be considered for acceptance at PAAR.\
However, there are a few questions/suggestions regarding the presentation that IMO could improve the paper, see comments.\strike0\striked0 \
\
Comments for authors\
--------------------\
\strike \strikec0 - One general weakness in the presentation is that the paper is full of bullet point lists, and the structure gets hard to follow in some places. Would it be possible to use numbers or maybe even unique identifiers for these? Especially, since some of them describe the rules of the format, and they shouldn\'92t be washed together for the reader.\strike0\striked0 \
- Section 2.2, page 3: given the recent developments in higher-order logic in TPTP and ATPs, would it be possible to reference Henkin models?\
\strike \strikec0 - Section 2.2, page 4: if C and Ax in the MEX definition are from Figure 1, can you refer to Figure 1 here?\strike0\striked0 \
- Section 2.3:\
    \strike \strikec0 - Page 4: It could be emphasized that this subsection already discusses the contributions of the paper.\strike0\striked0 \
    \strike \strikec0 - Page 4: \'93The models of the interpretation-formulae are conservative extensions of a subset of the models of the satisfiable formulae.\'94 - why just subset? Is it by design?\strike0\striked0 \
\strike \strikec0     - Page 5: \'93This approach is taken internally in Vampire.\'94 - while doing finite model building? This could be added to make it clearer.\strike0\striked0 \
    \strike \strikec0 - Page 5, footnote 4: I think readers would be interested in exactly why these people believe one or the other in more detail.\strike0\striked0 \
\strike \strikec0 - Section 2.4, page 5: In the first list, item 2 (well-formedness checking) should be first in my opinion.\
- Section 3 and 4 in general: it is not clear whether these sections describe only possibilities, guidelines, or actual rules to be added to the TPTP syntax for the interpretation formats. I think this could be clarified at the beginning of these sections.\strike0\striked0 \
- \strike \strikec0 Section 3.1, page 6:\
    - Is there a problem with the model if the problem already contains double-quoted elements?\strike0\striked0 \
    \strike \strikec0 - There seems to be a font size decrease in this subsection, causing all subsequent sections to have a decreased font size too, is this intentional?\strike0\striked0 \
\strike \strikec0 - Section 3.3:\
    - Page 7: Can you also handle polymorphic types with a finite domain of types?\
    - Page 8: If I understand correctly, the lambda abstractions are needed (and do not follow the conventions so far) because there are always infinitely many functions. Is this correct?\strike0\striked0 \
\strike \strikec0 - Section 3.4, page 9: in the predicate mapping example for Appendix C.3, it should be $less instead of peano_less\strike0\striked0 \
\strike \strikec0 - Section 3.5, page 9:\strike0\striked0 \
    \strike \strikec0 - I only realized in this section that the TPTP syntax was extended with a new \'93interpretation\'94 role. Although this is implicitly mentioned at the beginning of Section 2.3, it would be good to state it explicitly somewhere (beginning of Section 3?). Could you explain where this new role can be used, for example apparently not in model verification?\strike0\striked0 \
    -\strike \strikec0  Please put \'93\'85).\'94 at the end of this section\'92s last example, otherwise it looks like something is missing there. Same for the examples in Section 4.2.\
- Section 4, page 11: \'93A defined constant $local_world of type $world > $o\'94 - This sentence and later sections suggests that $local_world should be of type $world.\strike0\striked0 \
\
Minor comments:\
- \strike \strikec0 In general, I don\'92t like the listings/examples preceded by \'93\'85\'94, a colon would be better in most places.\
