Review #1B\
===========================================================================\
\
Overall merit\
-------------\
3. Weak accept\
\
Reviewer expertise\
------------------\
2. Some familiarity\
\
Paper summary\
-------------\
\strike \strikec0 The paper presents a format for expressing Interpretations in a wide range of different use cases. The paper motivates the need for such universal format, its requirements, and review its application with Tarskian, Herbrand and Kripke interpretations. The paper has a huge appendix (more than 40 pages!) heavily referred to in the paper, which makes it mandatory when reading the submission.\strike0\striked0 \
\
Comments for authors\
--------------------\
\strike \strikec0 The exercice of presenting a format for representing formulas or interpretations is not easy. The authors choose to provide the reader with a variety of examples using a huge appendix, and to refer to it when presenting examples in the paper.\
\
As a reader, I am not fan of that choice: while the reference is sometimes just a link to see the whole interpretation, there are other cases where looking at the reference is mandatory to understand the example: this makes the submission not self contained without the appendix.\strike0\striked0 \
\
\strike \strikec0 The CFP mentions that the submission should have up to 15 pages. It is not clear to the reviewer if the paper could be published with its appendix in the proceedings. If it is not the case, then the paper cannot be accepted in that form.\strike0\striked0 \
\
\strike \strikec0 Overall, the paper does a good job in explaining the rationale of the format in diverse contexts.\
The main issue is that a prior knowledge of the TPTP format is expected. It could be quickly reminded between section 2 and section 3 to make the paper more self contained.\strike0\striked0 \
\
\strike \strikec0 Here are a few remarks to improve the submission:\
\strike0\striked0 \
\strike \strikec0 - Page 5: "If a formula can be disproved from the HI-formulae then it is false in all the Herbrand\
interpretations determined by the HI-formulae."\
\
Unless I do not understand the meaning of proving/disproving in that particular context, I guess that a formula is disproved if it is false in at least one of the Herbrand interpretation?\strike0\striked0 \
\
\strike \strikec0 - Page 11: "A defined predicate $in_world of type ($world * $o) > $o to specify the interpretations in the worlds."\
\
$o is not defined in the paper, but looks like a Boolean type according to the examples, and confirmed by TPTP documentation.\
\
However, in the example later, we find "$in_world(w1,the Tarskian interpretation)". Is $o polymorphic to represent in general an interpretation, not just a Boolean value?\strike0\striked0 \
\
\strike \strikec0 - Page 11: typo\
subfomulae -> subformulae\strike0\striked0 \
\
\strike \strikec0 - page 11, the local_world constant is defined like a predicate ($world > $o). It should probably be typed $world.\strike0\striked0 \
\
