Review #1C\
===========================================================================\
\
Overall merit\
-------------\
4. Accept\
\
Reviewer expertise\
------------------\
3. Knowledgeable\
\
Paper summary\
-------------\
\strike \strikec0 The paper describes the TPTP format for representing interpretations / models.\
It provides a good motivation why interpretations are actually of interest,\
what forms they might take, what tools already produce some form of model,\
and what we can do with models. This is then followed by a presentation of\
the TPTP format for various kinds of interpretations, finite domain, infinite\
domain, typed, Kripke. A tool for the visualization of interpretations is also\
briefly introduced.\strike0\striked0 \
\strike \strikec0 \
My main concern is the length of the paper. It's 17 pages plus 44 pages of\
appendices. The first 17 pages also frequently referring to particular\
sections in the appendices. So, it doesn't seem possible to just publish the\
first 17 pages without the appendices.\strike0\striked0 \
\
Comments for authors\
--------------------\
* Page 3:\
  > A Tarskian interpretation [47] consists of a non-empty domain of distinct\
  > elements (not the Herbrand Universe \'96 see Herbrand interpretations below)\
  > for each type used in the formulae (just one domain for untyped logic),\
  > mappings for function symbols from tuples of domain elements to the domain,\
  > and mappings for predicate symbols from tuples of domain elements to\
  > \{true, false\} [48,49]. An overview of some ways of building and representing\
  > Tarskian interpretations is provided by [45], and [50] provides a comprehensive\
  > list of approaches. A complete interpretation can be used to evaluate\
  > all formulae that can be written in the language of the problem formulae, but\
  > a partial interpretation can be used to evaluate the problem formulae but not\
  > necessarily all possible formulae [51].\
  The notion of a "complete interpretation" does not occur in [47] nor in [50].\
  The phrase "complete model" occurs in [51] but is not defined. A "partial model"\
  is defined in [51] as a satisfiable set of ground literals (so probably not\
  what is meant here). The phrase "partial interpretation" does not occur in\
  [47,50,51]. I would suggest to formally define what you mean by these notions.\
*\strike \strikec0  Page 5:\
  "I believe that this verification technique works, ..."\
  The paper has four authors. I would suggest it's either "We believe" or\
  "\{Name\} believes".\strike0\striked0 \
*\strike \strikec0  Page 6:\
  > The predicate mappings are atoms, e.g., in Appendix A.2 ...\
  >  created_equal("john","gotA")\
  > Note that for a complete interpretation all function and predicate\
  > mappings need to be provided\
  Page 7:\
  > The predicate mappings are atoms, e.g., in Appendix B.2 ...\
  > ~ owns(d_jon,d_nermal)"\
  ~owns(d_jon,d_nermal) is a literal. This seems to be a systematic mistake.\strike0\striked0 \
\strike \strikec0 * Page 9:\
  > Appendices A.4 and B.6 show examples of splitting the interpretation-formulae\
  > in Appendices A.2 and B.2 respectively, which separate the domain\
  > specifications from the symbol mappings, e.g., in Appendix B.2\
  > the interpretation-formula ...\
  >   tff(garfield_domains,interpretation-domains\
  > contains the information about the two domains, and\
  > the interpretation-formula ...\
  >   tff(garfield_mappings,interpretation-mappings\
  > contains the symbol mappings.\
  tff(garfield_domains,interpretation-domains and\
  tff(garfield_mappings,interpretation-mappings are incomplete formulae.\
  I would suggest to write tff(garfield_mappings,interpretation-mappings, ...)\
  or tff(garfield_mappings,interpretation-mappings, F).\
  If the second alternative is chosen then it would be good to characterise\
  what F is.\strike0\striked0 \
